Principal Component Analysis

Dataset water.sand.all.LUSI.red.scaled

This dataset contains 151 individuals and 8 variables, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Study of the outliers

The analysis of the graphs leads to detect outliers that strongly influence the results. First we will describe these outliers and then we will suppress them from the analysis. Looking at the graph, we can note that 3 particular individuals strongly contribute to the construction of the plane. The cumulative contribution of these individuals to the construction of the plane equals 42.4%.

Figure 1.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) before correction. Highlighting of 3 outliers.

Figure 1.2 - Individuals factor map (PCA) after correction. Highlighting of 3 outliers.

Figure 1.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) before correction The variables in black are considered as active whereas those in blue are illustrative. The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

Figure 1.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) after correction

The individual 8 :

  • takes very high values for the variable(s) : PO4, NO3, NH4 and seston (variables are sorted from the strongest).

  • takes very low values for the variable(s) : secchi.

The individual 33 :

  • takes very high values for the variable(s) : PO4, seston, NH4 and NO3 (variables are sorted from the strongest).

  • takes very low values for the variable(s) : secchi.

The individual 58 :

  • takes very high values for the variable(s) : PO4, seston, NH4 and NO3 (variables are sorted from the strongest).

  • takes very low values for the variable(s) : secchi.

These outliers are suppressed from the analysis and a second one is performed on the rest of the individuals.

2. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 68.02% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 68.02% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is strongly greater than the reference value that equals 39.04%, the variability explained by this plane is thus highly significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 846 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 2 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 2 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (68.02% against 39.04%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

Figure 3.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

The Wilks test p-value indicates which variable factors are the best separated on the plane (i.e.which one explain the best the distance between individuals).

Figure 3.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 1, 4, 109, 2, 83, 15, 134, 9, 3 and 7 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis (to the left of the graph).

The group in which the individuals 1, 4 and 2 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable LUSI.
  • low values for the variables secchi and NO3 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The group in which the individuals 109, 83, 15, 134, 9, 3 and 7 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables chl_a, seston, NO3, NH4 and PO4 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.

The group 3 (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable secchi.
  • low values for the variables LUSI, seston, chl_a, NH4, PO4 and NO3 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The dimension 2 opposes individuals such as 109, 83, 15, 134, 9, 3 and 7 (to the top of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 1, 4 and 2 (to the bottom of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group 1 (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable secchi.
  • low values for the variables LUSI, seston, chl_a, NH4, PO4 and NO3 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The group in which the individuals 109, 83, 15, 134, 9, 3 and 7 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables chl_a, seston, NO3, NH4 and PO4 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.

The group in which the individuals 1, 4 and 2 stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable LUSI.
  • low values for the variables secchi and NO3 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

4. Classification

Figure 4 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals sharing :

  • high values for the variable secchi.
  • low values for the variables LUSI, seston, chl_a, PO4 and NH4 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 1, 2, 3, 4, 9 and 15. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables LUSI, seston and chl_a (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 7, 83, 109 and 134. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables PO4, NO3, NH4, seston and chl_a (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.
